        "references": [
            "HFL takes advantage of the multiple hops necessary in network topologies by using Aggregators to perform intermediate aggregation rather than directly traversing all links between Workers and the Coordinator with all models as in two-tier systems.\nWe use Flight’s LocalLauncher to simulate the benefits of HFL by comparing the total amount of data transferred over the network.\nWe initialize the simulation with a balanced tree topology with 256 leaves (i.e., 256 Workers) and vary its height from h=1,2,4,8ℎ1248h=1,2,4,8. We generate these tree topologies using the balanced_tree(⋅⋅\\cdot) function from NetworkX (Hagberg et al., 2008).\nThis function takes a height (hℎh) and branching factor (b𝑏b) as an argument, which we compute by\nb=2561/h𝑏superscript2561ℎb=256^{1/h}.\nGiven the balanced trees, we use the model sizes from Table 2 to numerically compute the data transfer costs for two-tier FL and HFL.\nThe mathematical details behind these calculations are presented in A.\nThe reduction in transfer volume achieved by HFL is shown in Fig. 7.\nThe benefit of HFL becomes increasingly notable with topology height, saving 60.13% in the case of a height of 8 with the ResNet-152 model. Fig. 7 also shows comparable test accuracy during training across all topology heights, though test accuracy becomes less stable as height increases."
